title: For Sale:  Nearly a Million rounds of Factory brass cased .223 and .30 Carbine
postcontent:
I am currently working with a wholesale liquidation company to resolve the holdings of the Former ammunition Manufacturer American Ammunition, or A-Merc.

A-Merc went bankrupt for several reasons, including Quality Control, and much of the ammunition that was being liquidated is scrap. However, the liquidators have a team of personnel inspecting every single round for sale. Every single round for sale gets tumbled, chamber checked, and visually inspected. Rounds that fail any part of the process are rejected, and sold off for components. Rounds that pass are sold in bulk.

The first of the rifle rounds that are part of the lot are brass cased .223 rounds. Most of the bullets (>95%) are 55gr FMJ with Boat Tail and a cannelure bullet. The other 5% tend to be 62gr FMJ Rounded nose bullets. All have a loading of approximately 23gr of powder. These rounds will frequently have hairline cracks on the neck - However, they will be safe to shoot. I've shot approximately 800 so far, with no ill effect. They are generally low quality brass, so I would not expect significant reload value from them. There are approximately 600,000 rounds of .223 that are being moved. 

The second rifle round is brass cased .30 Carbine rounds. These have a 110gr FMJ round nose bullet, and have 13 grains of powder charge. The brass on these rounds is better - you will have success in reloading the brass, though it is still not high quality. There are approximately 100,000 rounds of .30 Carbine.

There will tend to be cosmetic blemishes on some of the ammo. While the inspection and cleaning process will disqualify unsafe rounds, expect occasional dents or scratches that will not affect safety. These are from the storage and shipping of the ammunition. Both rounds will be packed and sold in bulk boxes to weight - the weight is determined to be a quantity over 1000 rounds, so expect some extra to account for variability in weight. 

Price on the .223 is $400/1000

Price on the .30 Carbine is $350/1000

I also have rounds that were rejected for sale, at deep discount. I must stress that these are for component salvage only, and not for firing. For the .223, expect to see a significant quantity of damaged casings, but a high recovery rate on the bullets (>900 per box). For the .30 Carbine, expect to see about 50% recovery on bullets or brass. Of course, all the brass is primed, which you can salvage, and all complete bullets have the powder. I do not have data on the powder, I'm afraid. Customers have reported loading the powder to the same loadings as factory with success, but I recommend disposal of the powder, without load data. 

Price on the Rejects are $100/1000, and the boxes tend to be very generous, on the order of 1050-1100 rounds. The rejects and ammo are sold completely as is. 

I conduct weekly pickups of ammo in Leesburg and Sterling. I am also happy to ship at only UPS ground shipping. Trades offers are welcome.

title: For Sale:  Half a Million rounds of Handgun Ammo - 9mm .38spl, .38Super, .32acp
postcontent:
I am currently working with a wholesale liquidation company to resolve the holdings of the Former ammunition Manufacturer American Ammunition, or A-Merc.

A-Merc went bankrupt for several reasons, including Quality Control, and much of the ammunition that was being liquidated is scrap. However, the liquidators have a team of personnel inspecting every single round for sale. Every single round for sale gets tumbled, chamber checked, and visually inspected. Rounds that fail any part of the process are rejected, and sold off for components. Rounds that pass are sold in bulk.

There will tend to be cosmetic blemishes on some of the ammo. While the inspection and cleaning process will disqualify unsafe rounds, expect occasional dents or scratches that will not affect safety. These are from the storage and shipping of the ammunition. Both rounds will be packed and sold in bulk boxes to weight - the weight is determined to be a quantity over 1000 rounds, so expect some extra to account for variability in weight. The handgun ammunition brass is low quality, but may offer several reloads before expiring. 

The 9mm is Brass 115gr FMJ round nosed ammunition. There are also some 117gr Hollowpoints, and 115gr frangible rounds that are generally separated, and sold separately. 

The 32acp is brass 73gr FMJ round nosed ammunition

There are two kinds of .38 Special - There is 158gr Lead round nosed ammunition, and 158gr FMJ flat nose ammunition. 

The .38Super is 115gr FMJ Round nosed ammunition

All the ammunition is packed in Bulk boxes of a 1000 by weight. The weights have been calibrated to exceed 1000 rounds, so expect several extra rounds. The prices are as follows:

9mm: $300
32 Auto: $250
38Special - Lead: $300
38Special - FMJ: $350
38 Super - $300

I also have rounds that were rejected for sale, at deep discount. I must stress that these are for component salvage only, and not for firing. All the brass is primed, which you can salvage, and all complete bullets have the powder. I do not have data on the powder, I'm afraid. Customers have reported loading the powder to the same loadings as factory with success, but I recommend disposal of the powder, without load data. Generally, rejects occur because of bad bullets or bad brass - expect a higher recovery (70%+) of brass on the 32, 38super, and 9mm. Expect no more than 50% recovery on either brass or bullets for .38spl. 

Price on the Rejects are $100/1000, and the boxes tend to be very generous, on the order of 1050-1100 rounds. The rejects and ammo are sold completely as is. 

I conduct weekly pickups of ammo in Leesburg and Sterling. I am also happy to ship at only UPS ground shipping. Trades offers are welcome.

title: For Sale:  Palmetto State Armory AR-15 with magazines and ammo
location: North of the QC's, Quad Cities, Illinois
postcontent:
I have for sale a slightly used Palmetto State Armory AR 15 with a 16" 1:7 twist chrome lined barrel, carbine length gas system, and m4 feed ramps. This is the same rifle as the PSA 16" M4 Premium Carbine. It was purchased as a separate flat top upper assembly and a separate lower receiver and parts kit. I assembled it myself. The lower receiver is marked "multi" and can fire both 5.56 Nato and .223 Rem ammo. It comes with a Rock River Arms chrome bolt carrier group.  This rifle has 200 rounds through it (170 rounds of .223 with 40 rounds being steel cased ammo, and 30 rounds of XM855 5.56x45 62 grain ammo.) without a single malfunction of any sort. It comes with 430 rounds of ammo (390 rounds of Federal XM855 5.56x45mm 62 grain FMJ ball ammo in the ammo can, 1 box of Winchester Ranger 60 grain .223, and 1 box of Herter's 55 grain steel cased .223) along with 6 magazines (3 steel magazines with gray magpul followers, 2 steel magazines with green followers, and one Gen2 PMAG). This rifle comes with an A2 rear sight with dual aperture for both close range and longer range shooting. The rifle will come in a US PeaceKeeper nylon zip case with 4 pouches for magazines and a zip-shut pocket for other necessities while you are at the range.

There was a spot on the ejection port side (right side) where tool marks were left while installing the roll pin while assembling the trigger guard. The spot was touched up with an off brand (not birchwood casey) gun bluing by a buddy of mine....but it is still able to be seen. I've attempted to show the spot in the last picture. It could be touched up with some aluminum black for a better match with the rest of the finish. In no way does this compromise the safety or function of the firearm. Other than that, this rifle is in fantastic shape with very few other handling marks (one on the opposite side of the trigger guard, and one by the bolt catch from my ring). More pictures are available if you are interested.

I have over $1,600 into this package. That said, I don't expect anybody to pay what I paid for it. $1,100 Cash only. All State and Federal laws apply (24 hour wait, valid FOID card, record of transfer, etc). I am not looking to travel a great distance for this sale, but with that said I go to the IL QC's 5 days a week for work. Would also travel as far east as Rockford...possibly DeKalb if you are from a suburb where this firearm is legal to own. I would consider selling to an Iowa or Wisconsin resident if you have a valid permit to purchase and/or a valid ccw permit along with the record of transfer. If you have any questions, just ask. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Collector's Dream-Winchester 94 .32-40
postcontent: Up for sale is a Winchester 94 chambered in .32-40. This rifle was made in 1907. It carries the standard buckhorn sights. One particularly interesting feature is the 2/3 length magazine, which is extremely rare. Only 12% of 94s were chambered in .32-40. Aside from cleaning some surface rust off of it, this rifle is in original condition. The finish is now a very attractive patina. The function is excellent. This classic example of the Winchester classic would make an excellent addition to anyone's collection. Price is 2200 OBO within reason. Reference gunbroker to compare prices, I think most would agree this is a fair price for a rare piece of history. Keep in mind that this piece will only appreciate in value, and is an investment. I would be happy to e-mail further pictures or answer any questions to anyone seriously interested. Only wanting a FTF in Indiana at this time. I am willing to travel for the right price.

title: For Sale/Trade:  HI-STANDARD Supermatic Citation SPACE GUN
location: Panama City Beach, Panama City, Florida
postcontent:
Space Gun! This .22 LR Series 103 Supermatic Citation has a 8" tapered barrel. Muzzle brake, & two weights. Mfg. Hamden Conn. S# 1260121. Condition 95 %. Phone 850 six0two4six6three  REDACTED $1100.00 plus $30.00 shipping and insurance. Original finish. Original magazine in excellent condition, mechanics & bore are perfect. Buyer to furnish FFL. Manufactured about 1960. Arguably the most accurate pistol ever produced.

High Standard Manufacturing Corporation of Hamden, Connecticut started production on their Model 102 series. These were radical guns for their time, and attracted a lot of attention with their futuristic design features. No other .22 pistols were quite like them. There were four basic models. The Supermatic Trophy was the top of the line, with a high polish and gold-plated trigger. The Supermatic Citation was identical except for finish, and had plastic grips instead of the walnut grips of the Trophy. The Olympic Trophy and Citation models were chambered for the .22 short cartridge, and were designed for Olympic rapid-fire competition. There were two different configurations of the Olympic series, one designed as an out-of-the-box contender in ISU (International Shooting Union) competition. It had a unique 6 ¾” barrel with an integral rather than a detachable stabilizer. At the Pan-American games of 1959, the .22 rapid-fire champion, runner-up and the entire 4-man winning United States team all used Hi-Standard Olympic Citations. Captain Bill McMillan of the United States Marine Corps won a .22 rapid-fire Olympic gold medal in Rome with an ISU Olympic in 1960. The fourth model of the 102 series was the Tournament, a no-frills economy model without some of the advanced features of the more expensive guns. Each of these models would accept different barrels interchangeably. Barrels offered were a 10-incher with an integral rear sight over the chamber, an 8-incher with integral rear sight, and a 6 ¾-incher with no rear sight. The rear sight was mounted on the slide on this model, giving a longer sight radius than even the 10-inch barrels. Many tournament shooters accordingly preferred this length of barrel. At Camp Perry, Ohio in 1959, Hi-Standards were used in a clean sweep of the first 3 places in the .22-caliber championship. In fact, the Hi-Standard guns of this period routinely outnumbered all other makes on the line, and in most cases were more prevalent than all other makes combined! The High Standard company touted these facts in their advertisements in the gun press, and sales soared.
